title: Malapit shoots another 79, ties for 8th
text:
Malapit shoots another 79, ties for 8th The Star Press 10:31 p.m. EDT October 3, 2015 Reece Malapit 181 CONNECT TWEET LINKEDIN 1 COMMENT EMAIL MORE 
As bad as the conditions were on Friday, Yorktown golf coach Nathan McClung said it was even worse on Saturday. 
Yorktown's Reece Malapit shot a 79 on Saturday in the second round at the IHSAA girls golf state championship at Prairie View Golf Course in Carmel, Indiana, mirroring her score on Friday and finishing in a tie for eighth at 14-over par. 
The cold, rainy and windy conditions returned to plague the course for another day, one where McClung said par felt like it should have been more around 77 or 78. 
"It was really impressive how Reece battled the last two days," McClung said. "These conditions are horrible. She avoided having blow-up holes, which was great considering how miserable it was out here. 
"She was mentally sharp and didn't have her best stuff, but was able to grind out that 79." 
Malapit had double bogeys on No. 1 and No. 10, but made birdies on No. 11 and No. 12 to bounce back. 
"I had a really bad hole (before No. 11), but McClung always says not to get down on myself and to look forward to the next hole and do better," Malapit said. "I was really excited after those two birdies, my morale was way up." 
Although she said her driving game is usually her strength, over the past two days, her putting was her strong suit. 
With the weather conditions causing trouble, Malapit said she stayed conservative yesterday, but tried to have an equal mix of being conservative and being aggressive on Saturday. 
On No. 11, she was aggressive and it worked out. 
"There were some holes I could have been more aggressive on, but look at how I did on No. 11.," Malapit said. "You have to be careful, you can't always be super aggressive or you'll get doubles and triples (bogeys). 
Evansville North won the team portion of the state championship, shooting a 651 while Westfield was second with 677. Lake Central's Alexis Miestowsi had the top individual score with 145, while Evansville North's Hadley Walts and Bloomington South's Cherise Otter both shot a 151 to tie for second.
